The grammar is extremely permissive: every terminal that appears in the string is produced directly by at least one non-terminal, and those non-terminals are all reachable from the start symbol S through chains of binary productions that form many inter-connected cycles (e.g. S ⇒ NT8 NT32, with NT8 and NT32 each able to grow to arbitrary length by rules such as NT8 → NT2 NT8, NT32 → NT1 NT21, NT21 → NT21 NT21, etc.).  
Because

• every token in the string has a generating non-terminal  
• those generating non-terminals are mutually reachable through the dense network of binary rules (providing the necessary combinations for any required substring split), and  
• S has four alternative binary decompositions, at least one of which (S → NT8 NT32) can expand—via the recursive rules just noted—to exactly the 37-token sequence given,

the string can indeed be derived from S.

Yes
